>Actually, most everything after the DC10 helped with comm..

Helped +-.  Cost a lot, as I recall.

>One code change I worked on for the DNXX and TOPS-10 was getting command
>line input to buffer. The DNxx would send off an ANF-10 packet to the 10
>for each character typed. The 87 code would often buffer tty input in
>packets because it did wait for a little while before sending the packets.
>Nonetheless, lines in local echo mode should have been able to buffer up
>characters until a break character before sending them off. Code changes
>to do this buffering in the 87 and netser were minimal. The challenge
>was scnser. Since this was a midnight (unoffical) hack (project), I
>resigned to let well enough alone.

ISC (Interactive Sciences Corp., Braintree MA. later ADP and then First Data)
got a complete network with remote echoing and a guaranteed-correct echo state
protocol working in the middle 70's.  I was involved in the protocol design,
hardware design & implementation, and the -10 side implementation.

We stole as much as we could (conceptually) from TELNET and added special case
hooks for TECO mode, etc., with echoing/break classes defined.  The network
links were (loosely) copied from X.25, and we had a simple routing algorithm.
Worked pretty well.

The network nodes those days were PDP-8's!!  The code there was Not Pretty.
When we got 11/04s we added a lot of remote peripheral stuff.
I designed and built interfaces for the 10 to the 11s.
We also added a connection-based NFS-like network file system before pretty much
anyone else that worked for and from the 11s and the 10s.

The SCNSER changes were not too bad, and mostly improved the clarity
of the logic.  Basically we reduced the number of points where echoing behavior
could change, and then it was pretty easy.  Researching the defined behavior
was harder!

We had customers multiplexed across a single 9600 baud line to San Francisco
(expensive in those days!) and they got local echoing that worked.
We could also drive a roomful of 9600 baud terminals at full bore (well, 6 to
8 from a KA-10, more from a KI).

When KLs came out we decided not to migrate the technology because we didn't
want to deal with the KL's interface to 11s, and the company didn't want to
spend money on software development.

Oh well; we -should- have publicized the technology at the time.  Dunno if DEC
would have looked at it - NIH.  It worked better than LAT.
