>Eric Smith (eric@goonsquad.spies.com) wrote:
>: In article <45j703$3qq@newsbf02.news.aol.com> jmfbah@aol.com (JMFBAH) writes:
>: > That reminds me of  a fixed head disk that was used for swapping (could it
>: > have been a Burroughs?) on a 48K KA system.  There were ways to cause it
>: > to walk across the floor to the other side of the room.

>: A *FIXED*HEAD* disk?  What could the software do to make it move?

Barbara is probably a little confused.  Indeed, the fix head disks generally
sat there and you never knew they were running.  The early removable disk
pack drives were indeed the stuff of walk-around-the-room lore.  Just watching
them do random seeks was enough to disuade me from searching for their
resonant frequency!

>Didn't the Illiac IV have fixed head disks? They would have a head
>dedicated to a track for fast roll in/roll out. 

Could well have.  Fixed head disks were common in that era.  The -10 had three:

RM10B	The Bryant drum, actually a truncated cone.  As it came up to speed,
	centrifugal force lifted the drum to the heads providing a gentle
	start to flying heads.  Its card cage had point-to-point soldered
	wiring, the only peripheral in the -10 line that wasn't
	wirewrapped, as far as I know.  It was so fast, just a few usec
	per word (I forget the exact speed), that TOPS-10 would swap
	programs to the drum and read them back instead of running the
	memory shuffler when some other program wanted to grow.

RD10	The Burroughs disk. About 4 feet in diameter.

RF10?	About the size of a RP02 platter in a rack mountable box.  Latest
	of the three.

I don't have the specs of any of these at my finger tips.  They were certainly
good technology for swapping and paging in a memory starved system.


As for a home-grown hardware diagnostic, we had occasional parity errors
at CMU in our 64K Ampex core memory, and DEC's diagnostics never found
anything.  So I wrote a standalone diagnostic that had three processes.
The first created one of several patterns, wrote it to the RM10B, read it
back, and checked it.  The second did the same to the maintenance tracks
of a RP02.  The third just ran on the CPU creating and checking the patterns.
The processes were essentially just the interrupt routines, so the CPU
test kept getting interrupted.  The -10 never looked busier than when the
diagnostic was running, and turning off the computer room lights made it
even more impressive.  The RM10B, its controller (RC10) and channel (DF10)
ran through the patterns quickly, the RP02, its controller (RP10) and
DF10 did so more slowly.  The memory boxes jumped back and forth, sometimes
pausing as all the transfers went to other boxes, and CPU looked like it
was sweating, never sticking with any pattern for more than a fraction
of a second.

And it even found some memory errors, around the time we concluded that
some of the wires in the Ampex memory were failing due to turbulence from
the cooling fans.  Fortunately they were 16Kx20 core planes, so we had
some spare strings we could use before we had to get it completely
restrung.
