On 23Oct95, Mark Crispin wrote:
<The BLISS compiler was written in BLISS, as (I think) was the FORTRAN
<compiler.  Since most people didn't have FORTRAN compiler sources, it
<didn't really matter that much that it was unmaintainable.

From TOPS10's point of view, it did matter that BLISS was unmaintainable. 
BLISS-10 (the FORTRAN-10 compiler was written with this) had a bad bug; I
don't remember the specific details but I think it had to do with the use
bits being diddled with by that naughty compiler.  BLISS-10 was so
unmaintainable that TW agreed to "fix" the bug in the monitor rather than
force the maintainance group to distribute the real fix in BLISS-10.

Since I was the person who designed, spec'ed, and implemented the build
procedures on TOPS10 since 7.01,  I can assure you that all those pieces
that used any flavor in BLISS were a pain in the a--!  Since we
distributed sources (TOPS20 didn't so it didn't have as much of a
problem), I had to make sure that what the customer got on tape (the
binaries) was bit-for-bit identical if he decided to build it himself. 
The stuff written in BLISS was almost impossible to enforce this rule.

/BAH


