Long after John C left, the company's main timesharing system, a dual KI10,
was down there (between the salvage area and the Maynard sewer connection).
Lighting was fluourescent lights hanging from the ceiling (essentially cheap
shop lights without reflectors).  One day, a Telco person was stringing new
TTY cables.  He'd toss the cable over the lights, and tack it to the ceiling
later.  On one toss he dislodged a bulb which fell down on top of a RP04
(3?) drive's window.  The window didn't break, but the bulb shattered, of
course.

The Telco guy froze, suddenly aware that he may have done something Very
Bad.  I immediately took a couple steps to the drive to hit the off button,
but a field service person was closer and closing in too.  I figured the
positive pressure and window seals would have kept the glass shards out, but
with the pack inspector we saw half a dozen concentric scratches at various
radii.  While it wasn't one of our permanently mounted file systems, it
often in use, and the OS immediately start complaining that it could no
longer talk to the drive.

Never saw that particular Telco guy again.
