assure you that the FHA on KA system 101 was an RD-10 Burroughs fixed
head disk. Ah, how many times did I watch the fiendish service people replace
heads on that beast . . . I think I even still have one of the bad heads in a box
somewhere with the rest of my PDP-10 memorabilia.

One thing I donated to Stevens that I now wish I had taken with me is the
NUL-10, which as you may remember sat on top of the TD-10 (DECTape
controller). It would spell out "TILT" in its lights when it lost power, and
randomly flashed the lights when it had power. It was made of a genuine
TD-10 faceplate with neon bulbs populating the indicators, and had enough
lights to be interesting. One of the F.E.s gave me the TD-10 faceplate
because of a standing joke I had about building a broken PDP-10! I'd collect
all the bad parts they extracted from the system that they would have thrown
out, and to this day I'm still working on it . . .

