    Ah yes, paper tape.  Recall that on the earlier PDP-1s, there was
    no disk, no magtape, no network/floppy/etc/etc.  Paper tape and
    the console typewriter were IT for 'permanent' storage output.  Of
    those two, only paper tape could also be read back into the
    computer, so it was the preferred medium.

    Off-line paper tape preparation was done on Frieden Flexowriters,
    heavy, noisy, electric typewrite-like devices with paper tape
    reader and punch.  As one might guess, correcting typing errors on
    paper tape was a challenge.  Restuffing the holes*, although not
    absolutely impossible, was difficult enough that it was done in
    only the most extreme of circumstances.  (It really was.  Honest.)
    More commonly, one would manually back the tape up to the
    offending frame and punch an additional hole or holes that would
    cause the frame to be ignored.  (On the PDP-1, a hole in the
    seventh column had this effect.  On teletypes, all holes were
    punched thus producing the RUBOUT character.)  Of course, if your
    one-character error was several frames back, you'd probably have
    to delete all intervening frames and retype from the point of the
    error to (hopefully) get things right.

    The Flexowriters also had the ability to nanofanfold the tape.
    Microfanfold is what you got from the high-speed readers on the
    PDP-1/6/10 if the tape stopped folding correctly.  Nanofanfold
    could be produced by getting the tape stuck in the Flexo's reader
    or punch.  The uninitiated might call it "crumpled", but we knew
    better.
    
    
    dlm


    * - Skeptics beware.  This really can be done, generally with the
    help of some Scotch(tm) tape.  Note, however, that what you could
    do depended on what would later read the tape.  The high-speed
    readers on the computer were optical, so a hole with reasonably
    clear Scotch(tm) tape over it would still be read as a hole.  The
    readers on the Flexos were mechanical, however, and a small, metal
    finger had to be able to pass through the plane of the tape in
    order for the device to consider it a hole.  These points had to
    be kept in mind when repairing ripped, snagged, torn, and
    mutilated paper tapes also.  Still, it's a long time since we've
    had a medium that could be read by a human being without the aid
    of any machine.
    


