I remember a few things about paper tape from college.

First, we had a minicomputer in our lab with nothing but an ASR-33.  The 
BASIC interpreter took at least 30 minutes to load via non fan-fold paper 
tape.  We had an old record player rigged up to rewind the tape onto a 
spool after the program was loaded.  Luckily, the machine had 
honest-to-goodness magnetic core, so the interpreter would remain in 
memory through power cycles, and we didn't have to reload too often.

Second: The output of the optical paper tape reader on our KI-10 could be 
conveniently aimed at a waste basket.  Good for reading results from our 
spectrometer paper tape onto disk. (Before the days of direct 
computer-instrument interfacing.)

Third: The chaff (?) from the punch made great confetti, and was VERY 
hard to remove.  I think my old prof still has a few bits stuck in his 
desk drawers from a prank 25 years ago.

Punch cards:  I hated 'em, and would still be a chemist today if that's 
all I'd had.  But they were wonderfully tactile.  I remember writing a 
program to display a card image on a VT100.  As you typed a line of text, 
black punches would appear on a video-reversed white screen.  Stole the 
-029 lookup table from some TOPS-10 sources to get the punch patterns 
right.  Never did simulate the punches drifting downwards into little 
piles at the bottom of the screen, though.

-- 
