My *hate* of punch cards (and *one* of the reasons I dropped out of
programming and took up journalism) was that, in 1974 we had two main
computers at the State U. of NY at Stony Brook,  a 370 and a KA-10.

Coming off three years of KA-10 experience, I took on Comp. Sci. 101 and asked
for an account on the '10 - and was ordered by my prof to do all my work on
the 370, cutting mt cards like all the other freshmen in the room containing
45 zero-feedback keypunches - using field-sensitive ALGOL.

Spoke to Bruce Maier, then living one dorm over and managing the LIRICS-10
through a DECWriter II. No problem.

Except with the professor.

Who didn't believe in timesharing.

Or any language except ALGOL, specifically as writ for an IBM mainframe by his
professor in his undergrad days, and his requirement that everything be
submitted *on* punch cards *with* the sheets resulting from the batch run from
the 370.

The next year, SUNY @SB decided to scrap both the IBM and the KA-10 for a
UNIVAC. The head of the selection team was hired by UNIVAC six months later.

Oh, I kept up with *some* computer work, occasionally dropping by LIRICS,  and
finding the odd 12 or 18-bit machine squirrel led away (like the second of the
two LINAC PDP-9s  that was used extensively to test and retest DECUS
kaleidoscope routines while the 128x128 ADC on the other machine collected
data.

Later a PDP-8 unused for years would disappear from an engineering lab only to
reappear in a dorm room running MIT Chess and spark local competition  for the
best "electronic fireplace" programs capable of simulating the closest thing
to "fire" on the front panel lights.

				dmr

