In article <4qsaqh$1st@kirin.wwa.com> jeverett@wwa.com (John Everett) writes:


>    Many new to the 36 bit world are unaware that those of us who built TOPS-10 
>    are offended by lumping TOPS-10 and TOPS-20 together and calling them Tops. 

    The TOPS-20 folks aren't too keen on it either.  :-)
    
>    starting to practice this sacrilege. Of course this is somewhat amusing given 
>    the general revulsion when David Stone announced at a Monitor Group meeting 
>    one day that the PDP-10 Monitor would henceforth be called TOPS-10. We just 
>    HATED the name.
    
    As I recall, both groups usually referred to their respective OS
    as simply "the Monitor".  And virtually nobody called TOPS-10 by
    that name until TOPS-20 came along and the distinction had to be
    made. 

>    We were similarly unimpressed when DEC decided on TOPS-20 for Dan Murphy's 
>    operating system. 

    So were we.  We were quite amazed that dozens of highly paid and
    therefore extremely capable marketing managers and vice presidents
    could labor and contemplate for weeks and come up with something
    that creative.  I could never have done that.  I guess that's why
    I'm (still) an engineer.

    As to the sources, it's interesting to note that sources were
    shipped with TOPS-10 as normal practice.  When TOPS-20 came along,
    those selfsame managers and vice presidents decided we had to do
    things the modern, businesslike way (read: like IBM) and NOT ship
    sources.  However, TOPS-10 continued to ship them, at least as for
    as long as I recall.

    I'm quite convinced that the real bottom line on all this is that
    nobody at DEC knows enough to deal with this, and they wouldn't be
    willing to bother if they did.  For similar reasons, I doubt DEC
    would go after anyone who had the sources and used them, even for
    commercial purposes, provided a few simple precautions were taken,
    e.g. removing DEC's names and trademarks.  Of course, I'm neither
    a lawyer nor a representative of DEC, so I take no responsibility
    for what happens if you try it.
    
    
    dlm
    


